import numpy as np 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
from empiricaldist import Cdf

sns.set()
sns.set_style('ticks')
df = pd.read_csv('haberman.csv')

Two Ways of Scatter Plots¶

In [0]:

plt.xlabel('age') 
plt.ylabel('status') 
plt.scatter(df['year'],df['nodes'], label="Year")
plt.title('Age vs Year') 
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Compute CDF, Plot CDF¶

cdf_age.plot()

PairGrid - New to explore¶

In [0]:
pairGrid = sns.PairGrid(df, vars=['age','year','status','nodes'])
pairGrid = pairGrid.map_diag(plt.hist)
pairGrid = pairGrid.map_offdiag(plt.scatter)

Facet Grid¶

In [0]:
sns.set_style("whitegrid");
sns.FacetGrid(df, hue="status", size=4) \
   .map(plt.scatter, "year", "nodes") \
   .add_legend();
plt.show();

Conclusion¶

The Data provided is useful for cancer prediction and gaining insights into historical data and taking necessary precautions. One can easily perform EDA on haberman's cancer survival dataset and gather inferential information for further data analysis and machine learning. I found the pairGrid and pairPlot most useful that describes the data in beautiful plots.¶
